# INTENTIONALLY ILL-TYPED — kept as the acceptance fixture for `Known(none)`
# diagnostics in the type-specialization spike.
#
# An `Enum.reduce/3` reducer must return the *bare* new accumulator. This one
# returns a tagged `{:cont, acc + entry}` instead — that is the contract of the
# `Enumerable.reduce` *protocol* reducer / `Enum.reduce_while`, NOT `Enum.reduce`.
# So `acc` becomes `{:cont, int}`, and the next iteration evaluates
# `{:cont, int} + entry`; `Kernel.+/2` has no clause for `(tuple, integer)`.
#
# At runtime this raises `ArithmeticError`. The engine *should* catch it
# statically and emit a located diagnostic, e.g.:
#   `+` is not defined for `({:cont, integer}, integer)` at Main.reducer/2.
#
# Target status: pinned in type_infer. The linked runtime graph emits a
# `type/invalid-operator` telemetry diagnostic at Main.broken_reducer/2 instead
# of falling back to Unknown/any. The well-typed counterpart is
# enum_reduce_named_ref_ok.fz.

defmodule Main do
  fn broken_reducer(entry, acc) do
    {:cont, acc + entry}
  end

  fn main() do
    Enum.reduce([1, 2, 3], 0, &Main.broken_reducer/2)
    |> dbg()
  end
end
